  <h1 class="mb-6">Architecture: FactFeed</h1>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Compare this to Project 1's architecture.</strong> GreenScape had no backend, no database, no containers. FactFeed has all three — plus a background worker and CI pipeline. The architecture document gets more important as systems get more complex. In later projects, you'll direct AI to generate the architecture, and your job will be reviewing it for over-engineering and missing dependencies.</p>
  </Callout>

  <details class="my-6 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary>Copy full architecture as markdown</summary>
    <div class="p-4">
      <CodeBlock copy>{`# Architecture: FactFeed

## Tech Stack

| Technology | Purpose |
|---|---|
| React 18 | Frontend UI |
| FastAPI | Backend API (Python) |
| PostgreSQL 16 | Data storage |
| Docker Compose | Container orchestration |
| GitHub Actions | CI — lint + test + build on PRs |
| Gemini | Automated PR review via GitHub Actions |

## Service Architecture

\`\`\`
External Facts API
       ↓
   [Worker]  ← Background process, fetches facts on a schedule
       ↓
  [PostgreSQL]  ← Stores facts with source and timestamp
       ↓
   [FastAPI]  ← Serves random facts via REST API
       ↓
    [React]  ← Displays one fact at a time, "Next Fact" button
\`\`\`

## Docker Compose Services

Three containers orchestrated by Docker Compose:

| Service | Image | Port | Purpose |
|---|---|---|---|
| backend | Python 3.12 + FastAPI | 8000 | REST API + background worker |
| frontend | Node 20 + React | 3000 | Development server |
| db | postgres:16 | 5432 | Data storage |

## Repository Structure

\`\`\`
factfeed/
├── backend/
│   ├── app/
│   │   ├── main.py          ← FastAPI entry point
│   │   ├── models.py        ← SQLAlchemy models
│   │   ├── database.py      ← DB connection
│   │   ├── routes/
│   │   │   └── facts.py     ← /api/facts/* endpoints
│   │   └── worker/
│   │       └── fetcher.py   ← Background fact fetcher
│   ├── tests/
│   │   └── test_facts.py
│   ├── requirements.txt
│   └── Dockerfile
├── frontend/
│   ├── src/
│   │   ├── components/
│   │   │   └── FactCard.jsx
│   │   ├── App.jsx
│   │   ├── index.css
│   │   └── main.jsx
│   ├── package.json
│   └── Dockerfile
├── docker-compose.yml
├── .github/
│   └── workflows/
│       ├── ci.yml
│       └── gemini-review.yml
├── Makefile
├── CLAUDE.md
├── BACKLOG.md
└── .gitignore
\`\`\`

## Data Flow

1. **Worker** runs on a schedule (every 30 minutes)
2. Worker calls an external facts API, parses response
3. Worker inserts new facts into PostgreSQL (deduplicates by text hash)
4. **FastAPI** exposes \`GET /api/facts/random\` — picks a random row from the facts table
5. **React frontend** calls the API on load and on "Next Fact" click
6. Frontend displays fact text + source in a centred card

## Key Decisions

**Docker Compose for everything.** One command (\`make up\`) starts the entire stack. No "install PostgreSQL locally" — the database runs in a container. This is how real teams work.

**Separate worker process.** The fact fetcher runs inside the backend container as a background task. It could be a separate container, but for this project combining them keeps the Docker Compose file simpler.

**No caching layer.** The database is small and reads are fast. Adding Redis would be over-engineering for this use case. If the facts table had millions of rows, we'd reconsider.

**PostgreSQL, not SQLite.** SQLite would work for this project, but PostgreSQL teaches you skills that transfer to real production systems. You'll use psql, write SQL queries, and understand connection strings.

## What This Architecture Doesn't Need

Because the PRD anti-scope is clear:
- No authentication or user accounts
- No fact submission or user-generated content
- No categories or search
- No WebSocket real-time updates
- No caching layer (Redis)
- No CDN or static asset optimisation`}</CodeBlock>
